Feature goal:
Allow a teacher to generate an invite code and a student to join that teacher using the code.
Also allow a teacher to consume their own invite code for self-testing, so they can bind themself to themself and later test assignment flows.
Role and other future product-level profile fields must not live in the same SQLite table as Telegram transport metadata.

Requirements:

## Domain rules
- One teacher can have multiple students
- One student can be linked to only one teacher in MVP
- Binding must be invite-based
- Invite must be one-time use
- If a student is already linked to a teacher, joining another teacher must be rejected
- A teacher may use their own invite code on themself for testing
- Self-join must preserve the teacher role so `/invite` still works afterward

## Persistence
Add minimal SQLite support for:
- Telegram transport users
- separate product user profiles
- invites
- teacher-student links

Required persistence model:
- `users` table stores only Telegram-facing metadata:
  - `telegram_user_id`
  - `username`
  - `first_name`
  - `last_name`
  - timestamps
- `user_profiles` table stores product-level profile data:
  - `telegram_user_id`
  - `role`
  - timestamps
- `invites`
- `teacher_student_links`

Important:
- Role must be moved out of `users`
- Role must be read from `user_profiles`
- Keep the solution minimal, but make it structurally ready for future profile fields such as editable display name
- If an old `users.role` column exists, migrate existing data into `user_profiles` during bootstrap in the smallest reasonable way
- Runtime source of truth for role must be `user_profiles`

## Commands
### /invite
- teacher only
- generates one-time invite code
- returns the code to the teacher

### /join <code>
- student uses invite code
- validates invite
- creates teacher-student link
- marks invite as used
- rejects invalid / already used invite
- rejects join if student is already linked
- allows self-join when teacher uses their own code
- self-join must create a self-link and preserve the teacher role

### /me
- should continue working
- should display role from `user_profiles`, not from `users`

## Structural rules
- Do not dump this into one existing file
- Do not turn `bot.py` or `db.py` into catch-all files
- Prefer focused modules/files for:
  - profile persistence / access
  - invite and teacher-student persistence / rules
  - invite/join handlers if appropriate
- Keep integration minimal and explicit
- Avoid over-splitting into too many tiny files

Minimal acceptable split:
- `englishbot/db.py`:
  - SQLite bootstrap
  - low-level Telegram user persistence
- `englishbot/user_profiles.py`:
  - profile persistence helpers
  - role read/write helpers
- `englishbot/teacher_student.py`:
  - invite persistence + teacher-student binding rules
- `englishbot/teacher_handlers.py`:
  - thin Telegram handlers for `/invite` and `/join`

